Germany: a budget fetish that comes at a high cost
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is under fierce attack in Germany, a country that has long been proud of defending the principle of central bank independence.
In fact, it was Germany that ensured this principle was incorporated into the criteria set out by the Maastricht Treaty, which defines the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the euro zone involved a change in political regime.
Thus, the independence of the Bank of France, during the ratification referendum of the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, was one of the strongest arguments in the campaign against euro membership.
In today's Germany, however, it has become a common practice, if one can say so, to put pressure on the central bank.
For several months now, even the Finance Minister, Wolfgang Schaüble, has regularly commented on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very heart of what constitutes the independence of the central bank.
Although he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price norm," in the old jargon of the Bundesbank), he nonetheless offers his advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should use them to achieve such a goal.
We are familiar with precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then the German Finance Minister, offered his good advice to the first ECB president, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's ultimate goal was to create, in effect, a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with typical Dutch laconism, replied that there was nothing incongruous about a politician expressing his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). "Yet – he added –, it would be quite abnormal to take [his] suggestions into account."

The respect for monetary policy independence has long been a central element of German stability culture.
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's requests to keep interest rates down in 1956.
At that time, France did not see things in the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was about to create the Fifth Republic, with a Bank of France that reported to the Minister of Finance.
But it was a different time.
Following the various crises that shook the EMU, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Had the old dogma become obsolete?
The Europe remains very vulnerable; the average citizen of the EMU has already lost ten years and, what's even more alarming, we are close to a critical situation.
The United States, however, are doing better.
Despite a difficult political deadlock to manage, they have managed to tackle the macroeconomic problem (weak global demand) they were faced with by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also better managed their banking problems, which were initially much more severe than in Europe.
(There is, of course, a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are, and the better they are able to fulfill their function: financing the economy.)
However, the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a finance minister than by the lack of support from the population.
In fact, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, particularly in Germany, calling for it to be subjected to greater pressure.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy lies in the unbearable burden it bears.
The less fiscal policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are de facto forced to take on this goal (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course, and allow the economy to stagnate, or worse).
The political result of this sequence is a very clear regression towards nationalism, both right and left, in all EMU countries, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And here too, Germany leads the way, with its obsession with the schwarze Null, the balanced budget, against all odds.
In Germany, deficits are viewed negatively, not only from an arithmetic point of view but also morally, even though this goes against sound economic sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, Germany's leading public finance specialists, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, formulated a "golden rule" according to which current expenditures must be financed, on average, by current revenues.
Public expenditures, and the resources they require, are justified by their usefulness.
This means that investments aimed at improving productivity – capital expenditures – can be financed with debt, the service of which is ensured by the growth of income and the associated tax base.
This classic line of conduct has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenses and investment expenses, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
This is important, because in Germany, approximately 50% of public investment expenses are managed at this level (a decrease from the two-thirds municipal share in the early 1990s).
These expenses are consistent with support for the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (mittelstand).
However, compared to the early 1990s and at constant prices, investment expenses have decreased by approximately 15%.
More than a decade ago, they were insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not how we prepare for the future, then this is how we undermine productivity and prosperity.
In short, the black zero goes against the desired goal.
The outdated infrastructure (although not as outdated as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Furthermore, the German leaders' fiscal frugality extends beyond German borders and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which does not have exchange rates to accommodate national peculiarities.
Of course, the European Monetary Union is imperfect.
But transforming the only institution willing to "do what needs to be done" to bring the EMU back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
Having states use, where possible, the budget space they have to relieve pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, has some room for maneuver in this regard.
